469,IssuesEvent,2015-06-04 03:17:29+00:00,4576441,kbandla/dpkt,200847,kbandla,,,opened,dpkt erroneously truncates packet with TSO,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/kbandla/dpkt/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/kbandla/dpkt/labels/imported', 'name': 'imported', 'color': 'FFFFFF'}]",[],0,"_From [liulk@google.com](https://code.google.com/u/liulk@google.com/) on February 12, 2013 18:16:08_

When running tcpdump on an interface with TCP segmentation offload feature, the packet length field of the IP header is set to 0.  This causes dpkt to truncate the packet thinking that there is no payload but in fact there is.

This problem is also experienced by WireShark users. http://blogs.technet.com/b/nettracer/archive/2010/10/05/bogus-ip-packets-and-wireshark.aspx Attached is a patch to tell dpkt not to truncate packet if the length field has zero value.

Note that in the case of IP6, jumbo payload will also set length to 0, but this patch does not add in support to parse the extended jumbo packet length header.

liulk

**Attachment:** [0001-dpkt-IP-and-IP6-fix-to-correctly-deal-with-zero-payl.patch](http://code.google.com/p/dpkt/issues/detail?id=101)

_Original issue: http://code.google.com/p/dpkt/issues/detail?id=101_",{},{}
