strategy = bt.Strategy('example', [bt.algos.RunOnDate(*dates),
                                   bt.algos.WeighTarget(weights),
                                   bt.algos.Rebalance()])                         

def comm(price, quantity):
    return price * quantity * 0.5

bt_gross = bt.Backtest(strategy, data, integer_positions=False, name='gross')
bt_net = bt.Backtest(strategy, data, integer_positions=False, commissions=comm, name='net')

result = bt.run(bt_gross, bt_net)
result.plot('d')
df_merge = bt.merge(result.get_transactions('gross'),
                    result.get_transactions('net'))`

Is this the intended behaviour? 
Is there a way of seeing the cash? 
Would the strategy always invest 100% into equity and 'borrow' the commission? (i.e. should the weights be (1-com) at initial rebalance?
Why would a single asset strategy constantly invested at 100% still generate trades?

