1878,IssuesEvent,2018-03-13 02:36:22+00:00,21343426,aboSamoor/pycld2,489034,msdos,,,opened,Problem with this lib in raspberrypi 3: can't install.,[],[],0,"```
arm-linux-gnueabihf-gcc: error: unrecognized command line option ‘-m64’
error: command 'arm-linux-gnueabihf-gcc' failed with exit status 1
```
Similar to https://stackoverflow.com/questions/36115835/how-to-install-polyglot-on-raspberry-pi-problems-with-compatibility

> I managed to solve this problem.
> 
> First you need to do is to download polyglot's source code:
> 
> git clone https://github.com/aboSamoor/polyglot
> Then edit setup.py:
> 
> nano polyglot/pycld2/setup.py
> Change this line:
> 
> extra_compile_args=['-w', '-O2', '-m64', '-fPIC'],
> to:
> 
> extra_compile_args=['-w', '-O2', '-fPIC'],
> Install PYCLD2:
> 
> sudo ./setup.py install
> Install polyglot:
> 
> cd ..
> sudo ./setup.py install

Can we use the same approach as https://github.com/Theano/Theano/pull/3544/files to fix the `setup.py` to make it possible to compile in raspberrypi as well? Manually doing what's in the stackoverflow link it works.",{},{}
1895,IssuesEvent,2018-02-18 18:50:50+00:00,9923468,boppreh/keyboard,20151094,pjmtavares,,,opened,Question: what's the correct usage of 'get_typed_strings'?,[],[],0,"Hi boppreh, everyone... Congratulation on 'keyboard', excellent work!

I'm trying to save all the words I type at my computer to a file, in an endless loop, for personal time tracking. I managed to do this with 'pyHook', at first, but had to patch my copy to avoid breaking dead keys, rebuild it, and write quite some code to deduce which strings I typed in spite of edits. Then I discovered 'keyboard', which I found quite good, and started migrating my code to it. I thought  'get_typed_strings' might also already do a good part of what I was implementing, so I tried using it. 

I'm not experienced in generators, but after reading I couple of introductions, I wrote the following example code:
```
import keyboard

record = keyboard.start_recording()
words = keyboard.get_typed_strings(record)

while True:
    word = next(words)
    print(word)
```
However, I get an error: `AttributeError: 'Queue' object has no attribute 'name'`

If 'get_typed_strings' can be used in the way I intend, can someone please tell me what I'm doing wrong? Thank you for your time!",{},{}
1898,IssuesEvent,2017-02-02 01:37:10+00:00,9923468,boppreh/keyboard,1559801,Hyphen-ated,,,opened,Use a build server for automated testing?,[],[],0,"This library advertises python 2 compatibility but it looks like the latest release had zero testing on python 2, since it doesn't work at all.

I tried setting up travis-ci to run keyboard's test suite on python 2 and 3, and got it working pretty easily. Check it out: https://github.com/Hyphenated-integrations/keyboard/commits/master

https://travis-ci.org/Hyphenated-integrations/keyboard

When I revert the recent fix to the py2 issue, the py2 travis build fails! Cool! I don't know why it times out rather than giving an error message, but that's not a huge deal. It still means the code is broken. 

travis-ci is free for open source projects, so: consider doing this officially to help make fewer bad releases?",{},{}
