3015,IssuesEvent,2018-03-30 16:09:32+00:00,59235,mkleehammer/pyodbc,27421,mkleehammer,,,closed,"Expected bytes, string found (works in 4.0.21, fails in 4.0.22)",[],[],10,"Please first make sure you have looked at:

* Documentation: https://github.com/mkleehammer/pyodbc/wiki
* Other issues

### Environment

To diagnose, we usually need to know the following, including version numbers.  On Windows, be
sure to specify 32-bit Python or 64-bit:

- Python: 3.6.4
- pyodbc: 4.0.22
- OS: linux x86_64
- DB: sqlite3
- driver: /usr/lib64/libsqlite3odbc.so

### Issue

This code:
```
import pyodbc
cnxn = pyodbc.connect('Driver=SQLite3;Database=data.sqlite')
cursor = cnxn.cursor()
cursor.execute('select y from x where y = ?', 7)
row = cursor.fetchone()
print(row)
```
fails with the error:
```
TypeError: expected bytes, str found

The above exception was the direct cause of the following exception:

Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""a.py"", line 4, in <module>
    cursor.execute('select y from x where y = ?', 7)
SystemError: <class 'pyodbc.ProgrammingError'> returned a result with an error set
```

The database is:
```
sqlite> create table x (y int);
sqlite> insert into x values (7);
sqlite> insert into x values (3);
```

It works with 4.0.21 and everything else the same.",{},{}
