3903,IssuesEvent,2018-03-08 08:28:57+00:00,38987911,jmcarp/flask-apispec,1767010,lafrech,,,opened,How to use Rule.defaults attribute?,[],[],0,"`argument_to_param` deals with the `defaults` attribute of the `Rule` object: https://github.com/jmcarp/flask-apispec/blob/master/flask_apispec/paths.py#L43.

```python
if rule.defaults and argument in rule.defaults:
    param['default'] = rule.defaults[argument]
```

What's a real-life use case for this?

Here's what [the docs](http://werkzeug.pocoo.org/docs/0.14/routing/#werkzeug.routing.Rule) say about this `defaults` attribute:

> An optional dict with defaults for other rules with the same endpoint. This is a bit tricky but useful if you want to have unique URLs:
> 
> ```python
>     url_map = Map([
>         Rule('/all/', defaults={'page': 1}, endpoint='all_entries'),
>         Rule('/all/page/<int:page>', endpoint='all_entries')
>     ])
> ```

However, multiple rule for same endpoint is explicitly unsupported by apispec:

https://github.com/marshmallow-code/apispec/blob/dev/apispec/ext/flask.py#L91

> ```python
>     # WARNING: Assume 1 rule per view function for now
>     rule = current_app.url_map._rules_by_endpoint[endpoint][0]
>     return rule
> ```

(Also see https://github.com/marshmallow-code/apispec/issues/181.)

Is there something I'm missing?",{},{}
3904,IssuesEvent,2017-04-18 15:27:46+00:00,7433211,jmcnamara/XlsxWriter,15678442,zweger,,,opened,Issue writing Unicode noncharacters,[],[],0,"Writing the Unicode noncharacters U+FFFE/U+FFFF creates an invalid Excel file. Excel prompts: 
```We found a problem with some content in 'file.xlsx'. Do you want to try to recover as much as we can? If you trust the source of this workbook, click Yes.```

[W3C's XML Recommendation](https://www.w3.org/TR/xml/#charsets) excludes U+FFFE, U+FFFF from the valid character range. I believe the other excluded characters are already escaped by `xlsxwriter`, or not possible (as is the case for the Unicode surrogates U+D800-U+DFFF).

```
import xlsxwriter

workbook = xlsxwriter.Workbook('unicode_noncharacters.xlsx')
worksheet = workbook.add_worksheet()
worksheet.write_rich_string(0, 0, ""\ufffe"")
worksheet.write_rich_string(1, 0, ""\uffff"")
workbook.close()

# Separate code path
workbook = xlsxwriter.Workbook('unicode_noncharacters_optimized.xlsx', {'constant_memory': True})
worksheet = workbook.add_worksheet()
worksheet.write_rich_string(0, 0, ""\ufffe"")
worksheet.write_rich_string(1, 0, ""\uffff"")
workbook.close()
```

I believe the fix is as simple as adding `\uFFFE\uFFFF` to the character classes in `sharedstrings.py:95` and `worksheet.py:5219`.",{},{}
3919,IssuesEvent,2015-04-06 11:25:40+00:00,7433211,jmcnamara/XlsxWriter,310608,endeepak,,,opened,List validations removed for excel with 100k rows,[],[],0,"The excel opens file with error

![error](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/310608/7003720/e6ad40dc-dc7c-11e4-97a9-3af8290b7570.png)

Content of xml is 

```xml
<?xml version=""1.0"" encoding=""UTF-8"" standalone=""yes""?>
<recoveryLog xmlns=""http://schemas.openxmlformats.org/spreadsheetml/2006/main""> 
  <logFileName>error081281_01.xml</logFileName>
  <summary>Errors were detected in file 'C:\foo.xlsx'</summary>
  <removedFeatures summary=""Following is a list of removed features:"">
    <removedFeature>Removed Feature: Data validation from /xl/worksheets/sheet1.xml part</removedFeature>
  </removedFeatures>
</recoveryLog>
```

This issue is similar to https://github.com/jmcnamara/XlsxWriter/issues/89. But the content of my validation list does not exceed 255 character. I have pasted script below to create a test file to reproduce this error.

```py
import sys, random, string
from xlsxwriter import Workbook

options_list = [[""Foo 1""],
                [""Foo 1"", ""Foo 2"", ""Foo 3""], 
                [""Foo 1"", ""Foo 2"", ""Foo 3"", ""Foo 4""],
                [""Foo 1"", ""Foo 2"", ""Foo 3"", ""Foo 4"" ,""Foo 5""]]


def random_string(length=20):
    return ''.join(random.choice(string.ascii_uppercase + string.digits) for _ in range(length))


def create_file(number_of_rows):
    workbook = Workbook(""large_file.xlsx"")
    sheet = workbook.add_worksheet()

    for column_index, column in enumerate(['Column 1', 'Column 2']):
        sheet.write(0, column_index, column)
        sheet.set_column(column_index, column_index, 25)

    for row_index in range(1, number_of_rows):
        options = random.choice(options_list)
        sheet.write(row_index, 0, random_string())
        sheet.write(row_index, 1, random.choice(options))
        sheet.data_validation(row_index, 1, row_index, 1, {'validate': 'list', 'source': options})
    workbook.close()

if  __name__ == ""__main__"":
    create_file(number_of_rows=100000)
```

