4310,IssuesEvent,2015-03-29 20:10:16+00:00,21588191,coddingtonbear/jirafs,527661,coddingtonbear,,,closed,"Separate concepts of ""ignore"" from ""local only"".",[],[],1,"Currently, the only way to prevent a document from being uploaded is to make sure that its path matches a glob stored in a file named `.jirafs_ignore`.  When files match said globs, they will not be uploaded, but will continue to be tracked by the underlying git repository.

This becomes a little inconvenient (or, at best, strange) when things like, say, virtual environments, exist per-project, or runnable python files (which write, at runtime, a corresponding `.pyc` file) slightly pollute a ticket folder.  In those cases, it might be best to not track the file at all -- not even in the underlying git repository.

This issue will change things such that:

1. `.jirafs_ignore` will list globs of files that should not be tracked *at* *all* (rather than files that should only be tracked locally).
2. A new file, `.jirafs_local` will list globs of files that should only be tracked locally (and not uploaded to JIRA).",{},{}
4317,IssuesEvent,2018-06-27 19:30:07+00:00,71888065,cr0hn/aiohttp-swagger,9099245,dnwarnock,,,opened,Static UI assets reference malformed when using sub apps,[],[],0,"Swagger UI static assets are set to

`<link href=""/doc/swagger_static/css/typography.css"" media=""screen"" rel=""stylesheet"" type=""text/css"">`

when they should actually live at 

`<link href=""/api/v1/doc/swagger_static/css/typography.css"" media=""screen"" rel=""stylesheet"" type=""text/css"">`

if `setup_swagger` is called on a sub app like:

```
   setup_app(v1)
    setup_swagger(
        v1,
        swagger_url='/doc',
        swagger_from_file=""v1_swagger.json"",
        api_base_url='/api/v1'
    )
    app = web.Application()
    app.add_subapp('/api/v1', v1)
```
FIX:

`setup_swagger` should set `statics_path` = `'{}{}/swagger_static'.format(api_base_url,_swagger_url)` if sub apps are to work as specified in the documentation

",{},{}
4329,IssuesEvent,2018-05-13 18:42:03+00:00,8655936,exhuma/python-cluster,65717,exhuma,,,closed,Hierarchical clustering works under Python2.7 but fails under 3.5,[],[],1,"First, thanks for providing this library, it provided a very easy way to add a geographical clustering feature to a project I am working on (not presently in an open repository, but I am happy to send you and invite to view if it is of interest).

I recently returned to the body of code after a time and was trying to upgrade it from Python2.7 to Python3.5, and found that the HierarchicalCluster class throws an exception under 3.5 on data it processes flawlessly under 2.7.

I reduced the problem to a minimal test case, which follows at the end of this description.
I added some extra logging, and proved to my own satisfaction that the exception is thrown from logic around lines 5 to 25 of linkage.py which appear to relate to caching distance function results.  Under 2.7 the a and b parameters in this passage appear to be clusters, whereas under 3.5 they appear to be the key strings.

This was tested under 1.4.1, originally with the .whl file from PyPi, but also with the source unpacked to a directory alongside my code.

Test case follows:

from cluster import HierarchicalClustering
import logging

points1D = {
    'p4' : 5,
    'p2' : 6,
    'p7' : 10,
    'p9' : 120,
    'p10' : 121,
    'p11' : 119,
}

logging.basicConfig(level=logging.DEBUG)

distance_func = lambda a,b : abs(points1D[a]-points1D[b])
cl = HierarchicalClustering(points1D.keys(), distance_func)
clusters = cl.getlevel(20)

print(clusters)



",{},{}
4331,IssuesEvent,2017-09-30 01:37:50+00:00,57872901,facelessuser/backrefs,1055125,facelessuser,,,closed,2.1.0 release,[],[],3,"Things went wrong with the original 1.1.0 + release.  It was meant to add 3.7 support, but the test suite just wasn't testing enough to ensure a sound release.  Bugs were found and were fixed right a long, but it shouldn't have been released in its current state.  Those releases were removed as they were for the most part broken, and we will shoot for a 2.1 release jumping the previous releases.  2.1 is close and much more stable, but we'll give this a little more time will be given to ensure it is a solid release instead of pushing out quickly.",{},{}
