7962,IssuesEvent,2018-04-05 21:50:22+00:00,648332,assimp/assimp,32344571,NebuHiiEjamu,265533,assimp,opened,Make StreamReader::Get<T> and StreamWriter::Put<T> public,[],[],0,"When dealing with formats, a lot of data blocks (file headers, for example) are read into defined structs, often byte-packed. IOStream::Read() does as it should, but if the endian is reversed, each field of the struct must be byte swapped. The alternative to this is to make several calls to StreamReader::GetX#() which seems ugly for packed structs. Get<T>() and Put<T>() seem to aleviate that problem, but they are currently private to their respective Stream classes.",{},{}
7968,IssuesEvent,2016-01-20 23:58:08+00:00,648332,assimp/assimp,2323156,kimkulling,265533,assimp,closed,Dangerus AI_DEG_TO_RAD/AI_RAD_TO_DEG definition,[],[],3,"the macro are define as:
```
#define macro(x) (x*delta)
```
so if they are apply to an expression like a+b they multiply only the last value..
this happen in the ColladaLodaer file with the expression:
```
AI_DEG_TO_RAD (std::acos(std::pow(0.1f,1.f/srcLight->mFalloffExponent))+srcLight->mFalloffAngle);
```
I don't know what the formua does maybe is correct as it is since mFalloffAngle is in degree (and is the only value that is converted in radians) and the acos results in radians, and you want the radians as results.. 

any way i think that is better define the macro as 
```
#define macro(x) ((x)*delta)
```

Thanks",{},{}
