8117,IssuesEvent,2017-07-18 17:46:24+00:00,24774658,boto/boto3,1010634,stealthycoin,327752,boto,closed,IAM AssumeRolePolicyDocument Service ordering inconsistency,"[{'id': 297119947, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/boto/boto3/labels/api-question', 'name': 'api-question', 'color': 'cc317c', 'default': False}, {'id': 217065744, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/boto/boto3/labels/closing-soon-if-no-response', 'name': 'closing-soon-if-no-response', 'color': '5319e7', 'default': False}]",[],1,"It appears that boto3 does not consistently preserve the order of an IAM Role's AssumeRolePolicyDocument's services as defined in a role's ""Trusted Entities"" in the AWS console.

To repro, create a role in the AWS console that can be assumed by multiple services, say `ec2.amazonaws.com` and `ecs-tasks.amazonaws.com`. Then run the following script a handful of times and notice that the order of the printed list is not consistent.
```python
import boto3
client = boto3.client('iam')
role = client.get_role(RoleName='MyRole')
print(role['Role']['AssumeRolePolicyDocument']['Statement'][0]['Principal']['Service'])
```

```
$ python test.py
['ecs-tasks.amazonaws.com', 'ec2.amazonaws.com']
$ python test.py
['ec2.amazonaws.com', 'ecs-tasks.amazonaws.com']
```

Is this expected behavior? We're using boto3 to define roles and policies in a git repo, but this inconsistency is resulting in more git diffs than we would expect. It would be great if boto3 always returned the same order, especially considering that it is of type `list` and not `set` which implies ordering.",{},{}
8121,IssuesEvent,2015-11-24 21:25:13+00:00,24774658,boto/boto3,190930,mtdowling,327752,boto,closed,OpsWorks connections requires region selection,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/boto/boto3/labels/closing-soon-if-no-response', 'name': 'closing-soon-if-no-response', 'color': '5319e7'}]",[],5,"The following worked in boto:

```
import boto
ow = boto.connect_opsworks()
```

Similar methods fail in boto3 because of region selection:

```
import boto3
ow = boto3.resource('opsworks')  <-- raises NoRegionError
ow = boto3.client('opsworks')    <-- raises NoRegionError
```

The AWS OpsWorks UI does not allow region selection and defaults to us-east-1 just like boto. I believe boto3 should follow the guide here ;)",{},{}
8131,IssuesEvent,2016-03-01 18:11:15+00:00,24774658,boto/boto3,4605355,kyleknap,327752,boto,closed,Documentation error can cause individual to delete S3 data unknowingly.,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/boto/boto3/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': 'd7e102'}]",[],1,"The [documentation here](http://boto3.readthedocs.org/en/latest/guide/migrations3.html#access-controls) reads:

```
# Boto 2.x
bucket.set_acl('public-read')
key.set_acl('public-read')

# Boto 3
bucket.Acl().put(ACL='public-read')
obj.put(ACL='public-read')
```

Which, at least to me, leads to believing that the equivalent of `bucket.Acl().put(...)` for keys is `obj.put(...)`, however this appears not to update the ACL but instead replaces the object at that key with an empty file whose ACL is 'public-read'. What should be there is, I think:

`obj.Acl().put(...)`",{},{}
8134,IssuesEvent,2017-08-16 23:45:54+00:00,24774658,boto/boto3,1935727,joguSD,327752,boto,closed,[Question] - SyntaxError when using s3 client on aws-sam-local and Python3.7,[],[],1,"_Original issue was created on https://github.com/awslabs/aws-sam-local/issues/59_

_Apologies in advance if this is not the right place to open this issue, I don't have an extensive experience with aws-sam-local or Python, so I may be missing something really stupid._

I am building a Python logic to run on AWS Lambda and chose [aws-sam-local](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-sam-local) as framework.

I came up with a [simple Python test file](https://gist.github.com/maoo/2175a1c4b75a80c7271943591afb4920#file-test-py) which works fine when executed with python2.7:
```
pip install boto3 -t .
python -c 'from test import test1; test1(None,None)'
```

However, when trying to use `python3.6` as `Runtime` (as originally mentioned in [template.yaml](https://gist.github.com/maoo/2175a1c4b75a80c7271943591afb4920#file-template-yaml-L10)), I get a `SyntaxError: invalid syntax` on line `client = boto3.client('s3')`; the full history is on https://gist.github.com/maoo/2175a1c4b75a80c7271943591afb4920#file-error-log

Steps to reproduce the issue:
1. install npm
2. `npm install -g aws-sam-local`
3. Download `test.py` and `template.yaml` locally, same folder
4. `echo '{}' | sam local invoke Test`

Switching the `Runtime` to `python2.7` fixes the issue; anyone else having the same problem? Any idea what the cause could be?

TIA",{},{}
