9461,IssuesEvent,2015-09-25 08:23:55+00:00,2665618,inveniosoftware/invenio,119349,kaplun,1157480,inveniosoftware,closed,BibDocFile: doctype not correctly set/retrieved?,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/c_BibDocFile', 'name': 'c_BibDocFile', 'color': 'ededed'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/legacy', 'name': 'legacy', 'color': 'd4c5f9'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/p_blocker', 'name': 'p_blocker', 'color': 'e11d21'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/question', 'name': 'question', 'color': 'cc317c'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/r_wontfix', 'name': 'r_wontfix', 'color': 'bfe5bf'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/t_bug', 'name': 't_bug', 'color': 'eb6420'}]",[],4,"Originally on 2013-07-22

The doctype of a BibDocFile does not seem to be set up correctly any more when using `BibRecDocs.add_new_file(…)`:

```
$ echo 'test' > /tmp/test
$ python
>>> from invenio.dbquery import run_sql
>>> from invenio.bibdocfile import BibRecDocs
>>> bibarchive = BibRecDocs(21)
>>> bibarchive.list_bibdocs()
[]
>>> bibarchive.add_new_file('/tmp/test', doctype=""Foo"")
BibDoc(119L, 'Foo', False)
>>> bibarchive.list_bibdocs()
[BibDoc(119, 'Foo', False)]
>>> bibarchive.list_bibdocs(doctype=""Foo"")
[]
>>> bibarchive.list_bibdocs(doctype=""Main"")
[BibDoc(119, 'Foo', False)]
>>> bibarchive.list_latest_files(doctype='Foo')
[]
>>> bibarchive.list_latest_files(doctype='Main')
[BibDocFile('/opt/invenio/var/data/files/g0/119/content;1',  1, 'test', *, 21, 119, *, 'd8e8fca2dc0f896fd7cb4cb0031ba249', BibDocMoreInfo(119, ""ccopy_reg\n_reconstructor\np1\n(cinvenio.bibdocfile\nBibDocMoreInfo\np2\nc__builtin__\nobject\np3\nNtRp4\n(dp5\nS'cache_reads'\np6\nI01\nsS'docid'\np7\nI119\nsS'format'\np8\nNsS'cache'\np9\n(dp10\nS''\n(dp11\nS'flags'\np12\n(dp13\nsS'descriptions'\np14\n(dp15\nsS'comments'\np16\n(dp17\nsssS'cache_only'\np18\nI00\nsS'version'\np19\nNsS'relation'\np20\nNsS'dirty'\np21\n(dp22\nsb.""), False)]
>>>
>>> foo_file = bibarchive.list_latest_files()[0]
>>> foo_file.get_type()
'Main'
>>> run_sql(""SELECT id, status, docname, doctype FROM bibdoc WHERE id=%s"", (119,))
((119, '', None, 'Foo'),)
>>> run_sql(""SELECT id_bibrec, type, docname FROM bibrec_bibdoc WHERE id_bibdoc=%s"", (119,))
((21, 'Main', 'test'),)
```

This is tracing how ""Foo"" and ""Main"" get inserted into `bibdoc` and `bibrec_bibdoc`:
```
bibarchive.add_new_file(…, doctype, …)
 -> BibRecDocs.add_bibdoc(…, doctype, …)
   -> BibDoc.create_instance(recid=self.id, doctype=doctype, a_type = 'Main')
      # where a_type is left to default value 'Main'
      -> BibDoc.create_new_document(doctype, rec_links)
         # where rec_links has been built using a_type, because no docid was provided
         -> BibDoc.create_new_document(doc_type=doctype, rec_links)
            # where doc_type (Foo) is inserted as `doctype` into `bibdoc table`
            -> doc.attach_to_record(rec_links[i][""rec_id""], a_type=rec_links[i][""a_type""], …)
              # where a_type (Main) is inserted as `type` into `bibrec_bibdoc`
```

while `list_biboc(…)` is retrieving the doctype on the basis of `bibrec_bibdoc`:
```
    def list_bibdocs(self, doctype=None):
        [...]
            return [bibdoc for (bibdoc, attype) in self.bibdocs.values() if doctype == attype]
```

(and `self.bibdocs` is initialized in `BibRecDocs.__init__(…)` with `BibRecDocs.build_bibdoc_list(…)`):

```
    def build_bibdoc_list(self):
        [...]
            res = run_sql(""""""SELECT brbd.id_bibdoc, brbd.docname, brbd.type FROM bibrec_bibdoc as brbd JOIN
                         bibdoc as bd ON bd.id=brbd.id_bibdoc WHERE brbd.id_bibrec=%s AND
                         bd.status<>'DELETED' ORDER BY brbd.docname ASC"""""", (self.id,))
        for row in res:
            cur_doc = BibDoc.create_instance(docid=row[0], recid=self.id,
                                             human_readable=self.human_readable)
            self.bibdocs[row[1]] = (cur_doc, row[2])
```

 - Is `BibRecDocs.add_new_file(…)` the proper way to add a file?
 - Should `Foo` have been inserted into `bibrec_bibdoc` too?
 - Should `BibRecDocs.build_bibdoc_list(…)` builds its list on the basis of table `bibdoc`, not `bibrec_bibdoc`?",{},{}
9470,IssuesEvent,2015-04-14 07:11:16+00:00,2665618,inveniosoftware/invenio,1698163,lnielsen,1157480,inveniosoftware,closed,accounts: password hashing,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/c_WebSession', 'name': 'c_WebSession', 'color': 'ededed'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/master', 'name': 'master', 'color': 'd4c5f9'}]",[],8,"# Problem

Invenio password hashing is based on MySQL's AES encryption of the email address using the password as secret key.

This means e.g. that if the email address of a user is changed their password is invalidated.

# Proposal

* Explicitly store password salt instead of relying on email address.

* Support multiple hashing algorithms concurrently. 

* Support automatic deprecation and migration of hashes when user signs in.

* Support for overlay specific algorithms for password hashing.

* Deprecate Invenio's hashing algorithm in favour of SHA512.

* Implementation wise this will add two columns to ``user`` table: ``password_salt`` and ``password_scheme``. Additionally password hashing will rely on passlib library for all the low-level machinery.

# Implementation

See PR #2873 ",{},{}
9471,IssuesEvent,2016-07-04 14:42:13+00:00,2665618,inveniosoftware/invenio,189798,jirikuncar,1157480,inveniosoftware,closed,WebSearch: introduce 'bypassrglimit' action,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/c_WebSearch', 'name': 'c_WebSearch', 'color': 'ededed'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/p_trivial', 'name': 'p_trivial', 'color': 'f7c6c7'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/t_enhancement', 'name': 't_enhancement', 'color': 'eb6420'}]",[],1,"Originally on 2013-01-15

3ef9e5fa introduced the possibility for BibEdit users to bypass the limit for parameter 'rg' in search results. It is proposed to also let a distinct category of users to go over the limit, by introducing a ""bypassrglimit"" action (name to be refined).

Optionally one could even think of passing the limit as an optional parameter of the action, such that different roles could be granted different limits.",{},{}
9473,IssuesEvent,2016-07-05 13:06:04+00:00,2665618,inveniosoftware/invenio,189798,jirikuncar,1157480,inveniosoftware,closed,"Introduce ""useverbose"" action to configure ""verbose"" usage authorization","[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/c_WebAccess', 'name': 'c_WebAccess', 'color': 'ededed'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/p_minor', 'name': 'p_minor', 'color': 'f7c6c7'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/inveniosoftware/invenio/labels/t_enhancement', 'name': 't_enhancement', 'color': 'eb6420'}]",[],1,"Originally on 2013-02-20

In c11ccd29586b66d05a44d93f5369fa0323ca4ec6 the `verbose` URL query argument has been restricted only to superadmins.

There are however several cases in which some non admin would like to use it for debug certain situation in a production environment. E.g. to debug BibFormat templates or user settings, etc.

It would be nice to introduce a new `useverbose` action in the WebAccess stack, optionally parameterized with e.g. a `scope` keyword which could have values such as:

- `BibFormat`
* `WebSearch`
* `WebSession`
",{},{}
