11609,IssuesEvent,2016-05-06 21:34:26+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,157586,jsirois,3065172,pantsbuild,opened,Document AMI canarying,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/infra', 'name': 'infra', 'color': 'eb6420'}]",[],0,"There is now a 2 AMI setup for our Amazon EC2 Jenkins plugin.  The cloud is capped at 12 instances, the prod AMI is capped at 11, leaving a canary to fill the gap.  Normally the canary AMI will == the prod AMI, but if AMI changes are needed, it can be altered to point to a new one.

Document all this and add some debug output to our Jenkinsfile node step to print out enough identifying information to easily figure out if a node may have failed due to a bad canary vs a normal CI failure.",{},{}
11617,IssuesEvent,2018-04-23 03:32:32+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,46740,stuhood,3065172,pantsbuild,closed,Experimentally expose the rust Scheduler to v1 Tasks and test the integration,"[{'id': 268094252, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/engine', 'name': 'engine', 'color': 'fbca04', 'default': False}, {'id': 604059552, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/remoting', 'name': 'remoting', 'color': 'e99695', 'default': False}]",[],5,"The goal of this task is to experimentally expose the rust Scheduler to v1 Tasks so that they can directly/synchronously:
1. execute product requests (which can trigger things like #4397's process execution)
2. synchronously call into Snapshot APIs that will be implemented by #4585

Capturing Snapshots and executing isolated processes by poking the scheduler directly is sufficient for writing integration tests, and to allow for `compile` and `test` to be ported to remote process execution.

But this will be an *experimental/private API*, because it will not be possible to use it to cache (in memory in the rust Graph) any of these executions, since by the time v1 Tasks are running, we have already forked. #4769 covers the design for a longer term, cacheable integration between v1 Tasks and v2 products.",{},{}
