12893,IssuesEvent,2017-03-24 12:13:29+00:00,5196969,chardet/chardet,255672,deanmalmgren,6211498,chardet,opened,CP949 detected for what used to be ASCII,[],[],0,"Thank you for putting this package together and going through the hassle of merging these versions. Sounds like you've been busy!

I maintain [textract](https://github.com/deanmalmgren/textract) and we've recently had a few issues where the encoding detection is not working as well as it once did (e.g. https://github.com/deanmalmgren/textract/issues/107, https://github.com/deanmalmgren/textract/issues/133, and https://github.com/deanmalmgren/textract/issues/135) . When I revert back to version `2.1.1`, I am successfully able to detect that the file mentioned in https://github.com/deanmalmgren/textract/issues/107 is ASCII encoded. Later versions describe it as CP949, which causes problems for textract.

I would be happy to help address this issue. I am not familiar with the chardet codebase, so if you could point me in the right direction, that would be great. In the meantime, I can pin the version to chardet 2.1.1 which should hopefully resolve the issue in the interim.",{},{}
12894,IssuesEvent,2017-06-04 01:50:39+00:00,5196969,chardet/chardet,9766,blueyed,6211498,chardet,opened,Using unicode purple heart should not cause detection to lose confidence about utf-8,[],[],0,"I've noticed that the following file gets detected in a quite different way in chardet 3.0.3 compared to 2.3:

```
scriptencoding utf-8
"" :purple_heart: 💜
"" set list listchars=tab:»·,trail:·,eol:¬,nbsp:_,extends:❯,precedes:❮
```

chardet 2.3.0:
{'encoding': 'ISO-8859-2', 'confidence': 0.6680924803464797}

chardet 3.0.3:
{'encoding': 'Windows-1254', 'confidence': 0.5658124254347925, 'language': 'Turkish'}

This seems to be related to ISO-8859-2 being disabled currently, but I think it should be utf-8 after all?!
Remove the unicode glyph (purple heart, <💜> 128156, Hex 0001f49c, Octal 372234) makes it `{'encoding': 'utf-8', 'confidence': 0.99, 'language': ''}`.

(I've noticed this for the `chardet.detect` used in vint)",{},{}
