13154,IssuesEvent,2015-12-20 04:28:02+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,334496,ilanschnell,6392739,conda,closed,Bug when mixing CONDA_ENVS_PATH with win32 and win64 environments,[],[],1,"Usually, Miniconda installs environments in the *Miniconda/envs/* path.
Packages are usually copied in *Miniconda/pkgs/* and *Miniconda/pkgs32/* paths.

CONDA_ENVS_PATH can override the *envs/* path location to somewhere else, and then it creates a new folder *envs/.pkgs* to override the *Miniconda/pkgs/* AND *Miniconda/pkgs32* path location (Both will be used in the same location and this is the problem).
Since it does not create a envs/.pkgs32 path, changing between 32 and 64bit environments and downloading packages can lead to wrong package installation in environments.

The problem seems to be in this function:
https://github.com/conda/conda/blob/master/conda/config.py#L164
Since it is explicitly using '.pkgs' in the else statement, I'm unsure if this is really a bug or by design.
I found it to be a bug in MY usecase (see below).

**Configuration**
S.O.: Windows 7
Conda version: 3.18.3

**Steps to reproduce (Example)**
```
> set CONDA_ENVS_PATH=D:/tmp/A/envs2
> conda info
(...)
     root environment : D:\Miniconda  (writable)
     default environment : D:\Miniconda
     envs directories : D:\tmp\A\envs2
     package cache : D:\tmp\A\envs2\.pkgs
(...)

> set CONDA_FORCE_32BIT=
> conda create -n env64 python=2
> activate env64
> python -c ""import platform; print platform.architecture()""
('64bit', 'WindowsPE')
> deactivate

> set CONDA_FORCE_32BIT=1
> conda create -n env32 python=2
> activate env32
> python -c ""import platform; print platform.architecture()""
('64bit', 'WindowsPE')
> deactivate
```
",{},{}
13158,IssuesEvent,2018-08-26 16:37:34+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,10598343,mbargull,6392739,conda,opened,Solver improvements: 4) make solver runs more deterministic,[],[],0,"ref: https://github.com/conda/conda/pull/7676#issuecomment-415810372
> - Make runs of `conda.resolve.Resolve.get_reduced_index` consistent by ensuring the `specs` argument has a deterministic order (and maybe do that in a more intelligent fashion than just setting `specs = sorted(specs, key=str)` like I did while testing stuff.)

So, the order of the input of `conda.resolve.Resolve.resolve` is not deterministic for some reason. That way the way the solver is invoked can be slightly different from run to run. This should not have much effect on the result, but it would still be nice to get a more deterministic behavior here.
It's possible to achieve this in a ""hacky"" way by exploiting `MatchSpec.__str__` via
```python
     def get_reduced_index(self, specs):
+        specs = sorted(specs, key=str)
```
in `conda/resolve.py`, but this is obviously no clean solution at all..",{},{}
13164,IssuesEvent,2016-08-31 05:29:28+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,881019,dhirschfeld,6392739,conda,opened,activate.bat broken on conda-canary??,[],[],0,"My activate.bat/deactivate.bat appear to have been nuked and replaced with
```
@echo off
call ""C:\Minonda\Scripts\activate"" %*
```
```
@echo off
call ""C:\Minonda\Scripts\deactivate"" %*
```
???

Copy-pasting from the latest on github doesn't work because [L6](https://github.com/conda/conda/blob/master/shell/deactivate.bat#L6)
```
SET ""CONDA_EXE=C:\Python\Scripts\\..\Scripts\conda.exe""
```
results in
```
CALL ""C:\Python\Scripts\\..\Scripts\conda.exe"" ..checkenv ""cmd.exe"" ""py35-32""

IF errorlevel 1 exit /b 1
The system cannot find the path specified.
```

This issue I think is the extra `\`.

Replacing L6 with `SET ""CONDA_EXE=%~dp0conda.exe""` and substititing `s/~dp0\/~dp0` in both activate and deactivate appears to fix it.",{},{}
