13293,IssuesEvent,2018-03-06 23:43:11+00:00,12235583,elastic/curator,1020383,untergeek,6764390,elastic,closed,Current docs for Curator source install list missing/404 urls for dependencies,"[{'id': 186818252, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/elastic/curator/labels/Documentation', 'name': 'Documentation', 'color': '009800', 'default': False}]","[{'login': 'untergeek', 'id': 1020383, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars1.githubusercontent.com/u/1020383?v=4', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/untergeek', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/untergeek/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",2,"On the source install page in the docs:
https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/client/curator/current/python-source.html

A number of urls for dependencies are not working.


### Expected Behavior
URLs listed should resolve to downloadable tarballs rather than a HTTP 404.

### Actual Behavior
URLs are coming back as 404s due to either removed/missing tarball or possibly altered path to the file on the remote site.

### Steps to Reproduce the Problem

Go to:
https://www.elastic.co/guide/en/elasticsearch/client/curator/current/python-source.html

try the urls for the listed dependencies and some fail:

- https://pypi.python.org/packages/source/u/urllib3/urllib3-1.20.tar.gz
  - possible alternates:
    - https://github.com/shazow/urllib3/archive/1.20.tar.gz
    - https://pypi.python.org/packages/ee/11/7c59620aceedcc1ef65e156cc5ce5a24ef87be4107c2b74458464e437a5d/urllib3-1.22.tar.gz#md5=0da7bed3fe94bf7dc59ae37885cc72f7
- https://pypi.python.org/packages/source/c/click/click-6.7.tar.gz
  - possible alternates:
  - https://pypi.python.org/packages/95/d9/c3336b6b5711c3ab9d1d3a80f1a3e2afeb9d8c02a7166462f6cc96570897/click-6.7.tar.gz#md5=fc4cc00c4863833230d3af92af48abd4
  - https://github.com/pallets/click/archive/6.7.tar.gz
- https://github.com/certifi/python-certifi/archive/2017.1.23.tar.gz
  - possible alternates:
    - https://github.com/certifi/python-certifi/archive/2017.01.23.tar.gz
    - https://github.com/certifi/python-certifi/archive/2017.11.05.tar.gz
- https://codeload.github.com/elastic/elasticsearch-py/tar.gz/5.4.1
  - possible alternates:
    - https://pypi.python.org/packages/78/76/502a8e76e60d1fb3bf8326d94001465db8b7a4dd4df6c70b6f8ab3d87e33/elasticsearch-5.5.1.tar.gz#md5=91e0ddaf8952ef371005e9c6696b2f67
    - https://github.com/elastic/elasticsearch-py/archive/5.5.1.tar.gz

## Detailed Description
Potentially listed Install urls could be regularly tested to detect if they're not returning a valid url.
The equiv detail contained in the requirements.txt could be documented on this page to show minimum versions for a particular Curator version and potentially all dependency versions that have been tested as working with a particular Curator version.
",{},{}
13296,IssuesEvent,2016-04-22 18:50:49+00:00,12235583,elastic/curator,1020383,untergeek,6764390,elastic,closed,Weekly Index based on ISOWeek,[],[],2,"Hello,

I’m having a weekly index xyz_2016_15 (15 is the ISO week 15). The below command does not set up this index into the alias correctly

`curator alias --name last_month indices --newer-than 1 --timestring '%Y_%W' --time-unit weeks --prefix xyz_`

When I change the option to `--newer-than 2`, then it works.

What is the defined behaviour for curator, when I use the command to setup alias based on ISOWeeks

We are using Golang's time package, in which the [ISOWeek](https://golang.org/pkg/time/#Time.ISOWeek) based on ISO8601 returns week ranges from `1 to 53`.

Python's [datetime](https://docs.python.org/2/library/datetime.html#strftime-and-strptime-behavior) describes `%W` to be from `00, 01, ..., 53`

",{},{}
