13676,IssuesEvent,2017-09-01 12:34:21+00:00,13258039,aio-libs/aiohttp,356399,asvetlov,7049303,aio-libs,closed,Doc clarification -  StreamReader.iter_any() vs iter_chunks(),[],[],3,"It might help to clarify in the documentation the difference between [`iter_any`](http://aiohttp.readthedocs.io/en/stable/streams.html#aiohttp.StreamReader.iter_any) and [`iter_chunks`](http://aiohttp.readthedocs.io/en/stable/streams.html#aiohttp.StreamReader.iter_chunks). Currently it says

> Iterates over data chunks in order of intaking them into the stream

> Iterates over data chunks as received from the server

But it's not clear what the difference is between the chunks received from the server and the chunks that were taken into the stream.

My (naive) reading suggests the (almost certainly incorrect) interpretation that `iter_chunks` guarantees to preserve the chunks produced by the server under chunked transfer encoding, and yield them one by one. OTOH, since the `aiohttp` implementation is free to decide how to accept the chunks from the server into the stream (it can combine them or even split them), `iter_any` provides no guarantees about each yielded chunk is (other than that, if they are put together, they will of course combine to whatever the server sent).

BTW, this came up when I was reading the discussion about the chunked transfer encoding and `iter_any`, and specifically [this clarification](https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/pull/1900#issuecomment-302840811):

> [...] Chunked encoding is just transport protocol only, semantically it's a sequence of bytes without boundaries. Just like a TCP socket is semantically a stream of bytes while the content is transferred by packets. From my perspective partial chunks are totally correct.
",{},{}
13686,IssuesEvent,2017-05-24 00:47:07+00:00,13258039,aio-libs/aiohttp,10138830,zackelan,7049303,aio-libs,opened,ClientSession with default params caches DNS entries indefinitely,[],[],0,"## Long story short

ClientSession and TCPConnector, with its default parameters, caches DNS entries, but allegedly only for 10 seconds (https://github.com/aio-libs/aiohttp/blob/master/aiohttp/connector.py#L563). However, it seems to be caching the responses indefinitely by default.

## Expected behaviour

When the result of a DNS lookup changes, the cached entry should eventually expire and a new lookup should be performed.

## Actual behaviour

The old DNS entry seems to be getting cached forever.

## Steps to reproduce

This originally happened when a remote server changed IPs, but I was able to reproduce it locally using Docker, an Nginx container to act as the server, and this simple test script:

test.py:

```
import asyncio
import logging
import sys

import aiohttp

def main():
    logging.basicConfig(level=logging.INFO, format=""%(asctime)s %(message)s"")

    url = sys.argv[1]
    logging.info(url)

    async def test():
        session = aiohttp.ClientSession()

        # If you construct the session this way, it will work even through DNS changes
        #connector = aiohttp.TCPConnector(use_dns_cache=False)
        #session = aiohttp.ClientSession(connector=connector)

        while True:
            try:
                async with session.get(url, timeout=1) as response:
                    logging.info(response.status)
            except Exception:
                logging.exception(""error"")
            finally:
                await asyncio.sleep(1)

    loop = asyncio.get_event_loop()
    loop.run_until_complete(test())

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
```

Dockerfile:

```
FROM python:3.6.1-slim
RUN pip install aiohttp==2.0.7
COPY test.py /srv/test.py
CMD [""python3"", ""/srv/test.py"", ""http://test-server""]
```

Commands:

```
docker network create --subnet 192.168.42.0/16 test-net
docker run -d --net=test-net --ip 192.168.42.100 --name test-server nginx:latest

docker build -t test-client .
docker run -d --net=test-net --name test-client test-client

# At this point, test-client is behaving as expected - each request is coming back with a 200 status:
docker logs test-client

# Now, change the IP of test-server from xxx.100 to xxx.200:
docker rm -f test-server
docker run -d --net=test-net --ip 192.168.42.200 --name test-server nginx:latest

# In the logs of test-client now, there are TimeoutErrors and ""Connect call failed ('192.168.42.100', 80)""
# This goes on well past the 10 second cache TTL that TCPConnector uses as its default.
docker logs test-client

# You can ping test-server from within the test-client container, to confirm DNS is now returning the .200 address:
docker exec -it test-client ping -c 1 test-server
```

## Your environment

Originally discovered with Python 3.6.0 and aiohttp 2.0.7. Repro steps above test against 3.6.1.

I'm using Docker 17.03.1-ce on Linux 4.9.25, but don't believe that should affect the repro steps.
