13935,IssuesEvent,2016-07-16 15:38:26+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,151929,minrk,7388996,jupyter,closed,Notebook 4.1 causes matplotlib interactive figure to not execute next cell,[],[],7,"I am not sure where I best post this, here or at matplotlib's issue tracker, but as it is the notebook update that caused this, I am posting it here.

So with notebook 4.1.0, when using `%matplotlib notebook`, after executing a figure with shift-enter, this causes the next shift-enter to select the next cell but without executing anything.

A fig as example (the only thing I do here are repetitive shift-enter strokes):

![notebook410](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1020496/13202502/5eff4108-d89d-11e5-910f-d9fe7d51bd74.gif)

So you can see the cell selection advances, but the code cell is not executed.

Previously with older notebook version (and possibly this is also a bug in the matplotlib notebook widget), the cell selection stayed at the figure, and you also had to do a second 'shift-enter' to go to the next cell:

![notebook406](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1020496/13202510/ac2b3e5a-d89d-11e5-8061-1bb035bb873e.gif)

So possibly this was already a bug (or deliberate behaviour?), but now it is causing code cells not to be executed, which is much more annoying when doing shift-enter to go through the notebook.

I am on Windows 7, and using Firefox (but I see the same in Chrome).

",{},{}
13943,IssuesEvent,2016-07-05 10:58:25+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,327925,takluyver,7388996,jupyter,closed,Sending display_data after execute_reply,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jupyter/notebook/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': 'fef2c0'}]",[],6,"The messaging spec is not quite clear on this fine detail – can I send a display_data or execute_result message after sending an execute_reply?

It seems like the answer should, in all similar cases, be ""no"". As soon as a reply is sent to a request message, no future messages may that request as a ""parent"" -- so no more replies, no more display_data or execute_result, etc. Is this the case?

If so, it would be nice to make that explicit in the messaging spec.",{},{}
