15232,IssuesEvent,2018-01-02 23:10:41+00:00,112676803,apple/turicreate,902935,gustavla,10639145,apple,opened,Unable to create SFrame with non-ascii column name in Python 2,"[{'id': 766077328, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/apple/turicreate/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'ee0701', 'default': True}]",[],0,"I have been investigating unicode support in Python 2 and 3 as part of #110 and SFrame currently has a mostly consistent behavior, except for one thing that stands out as a bug: Creation of non-ascii column names in Python 2.

Python 2 supports putting both `bytes` (`str` in Python 2) and `unicode` into the SFrame and SArray. It is mostly accepted and printed as a UTF-8-encoded string and returned as UTF-8-encoded bytes objects (`str` in Python 2). However, it fails when it is a column name and entered as a dictionary through the constructor:

```python
>>> tc.SFrame({u'\u00aa': [1, 2, 3]})
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File ""<stdin>"", line 1, in <module>
  File "".../turicreate/data_structures/sframe.py"", line 833, in __init__
    raise ValueError('Unknown input type: ' + format)
  File "".../turicreate/cython/context.py"", line 49, in __exit__
    raise exc_type(exc_value)
TypeError: function takes exactly 5 arguments (1 given)
```

It's the same result for unicode string as for a UTF-8-encoded bytes string. It also fails for a bytes object that is not valid UTF-8 (e.g. `b'\xaa'`). It is only a problem when using the `SFrame` constructor, and there are several ways to get a non-ascii string in there:

```python
>>> sf = tc.SFrame()
>>> sf[u'\u00aa'.encode('utf-8')] = [1, 2, 3]
```

This error does not happen on Python 3 and the resulting SFrame can be saved from Python 3 and correctly loaded into Python 2.",{},{}
15292,IssuesEvent,2017-01-19 05:50:04+00:00,66823715,intel-analytics/BigDL,1995599,shane-huang,10941215,intel-analytics,opened,use generic option parser for commandline options,"[{'id': 514934524, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/intel-analytics/BigDL/labels/low', 'name': 'low', 'color': '008000', 'default': False}]",[],0,"We need a better way to organize the ways options are specified in all the examples and main application, specifically,
1. we need to provide default values to certain options
1. we need to make options less prone to errors (misspelling of option names, boundary/type check, etc.)
A general option parser (such as [scopt](https://github.com/scopt/scopt)) will be able to achieve the above. ",{},{}
