```

But I get this error:

> ValueError: Invalid conversion specification

And the error comes from [itp.py#518](https://github.com/Becksteinlab/GromacsWrapper/blob/7e8fe136f842d37aeca5532a78ca3dfa61c5d62f/gromacs/fileformats/itp.py#L518). However, version 0.6.0 works. So I think the commit 7e8fe136 and changing the string formatting is causing this issue.
",{},{}
15501,IssuesEvent,2016-12-12 16:38:28+00:00,33120392,zalando-stups/senza,10497901,lukasniemeier-zalando,11431876,zalando-stups,opened,Load Balancer Name Clash,[],[],0,"Currently senza generates the load balancer name from stack name and version. In case the name is too long, the stack name component is cut to 32 chars, see https://github.com/zalando-stups/senza/blob/master/senza/components/elastic_load_balancer.py#L18

This can lead to a situation in which senza tries to create two load balancers for the different stacks with the same name.

senza could fallback to generate random name in case the `name-version` combo is already taken.
",{},{}
15502,IssuesEvent,2015-10-27 14:55:23+00:00,33120392,zalando-stups/senza,1064524,tuxlife,11431876,zalando-stups,closed,Custom arguments problems are not displayed correctly anymore.,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/zalando-stups/senza/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}]",[],0,"Senza definition to reproduce:

```yaml
SenzaInfo:
  StackName: senza-args-test
  Parameters:
  - Arg1:
      Description: noop arg
  - Arg2:
      Description: noop arg
  - Arg3:
      Description: noop arg
  - Arg4:
      Description: noop arg
```

Now call `senza print` which requires properly filled in arguments of our definition:

```bash
$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION [PARAMETER]...

Error: Missing argument ""version"".
```

First regression comes in the ""Usage"" line: Senza doesn't print out the defined arguments anymore but only a generic ""[PARAMETER]"" block which isn't helpful. Expected message:

```bash
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION Arg1 Arg2 Arg3 Arg4

Error: Missing argument ""version"".
```

If specifying more arguments, the error message becomes random:

```bash
$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml 0
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION [PARAMETER]...

Error: Missing parameter ""Arg3""

$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml 0
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION [PARAMETER]...

Error: Missing parameter ""Arg1""

$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml 0
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION [PARAMETER]...

Error: Missing parameter ""Arg4""

$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml 0
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION [PARAMETER]...

Error: Missing parameter ""Arg2""
```

Also when specifying more parameters, it doesn't get better:

```bash
$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml 0 1 2
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION [PARAMETER]...

Error: Missing parameter ""Arg4""

$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml 0 1 2
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION [PARAMETER]...

Error: Missing parameter ""Arg3""
```

Previous behaviour was like that:

```bash
$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION Arg1 Arg2 Arg3 Arg4

Error: Missing argument ""version"".

$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml 0
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION Arg1 Arg2 Arg3 Arg4

Error: Missing argument ""Arg1"".

$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml 0 1
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION Arg1 Arg2 Arg3 Arg4

Error: Missing argument ""Arg2"".

$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml 0 1 2
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION Arg1 Arg2 Arg3 Arg4

Error: Missing argument ""Arg3"".

$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml 0 1 2 3
Usage: senza print [OPTIONS] DEFINITION VERSION Arg1 Arg2 Arg3 Arg4

Error: Missing argument ""Arg4"".

$ senza print senza-parameter-test.yaml 0 1 2 3 4
< all args passed, print! >
```

This regression is very unpleasant because depending of the amount of arguments of a senza definition, you cannot find out what to pass to the command and in which order.",{},{}
