17157,IssuesEvent,2018-05-26 04:57:49+00:00,51442999,python-cmd2/cmd2,218536,kotfu,17161025,python-cmd2,opened,preparse() and postparse() never get called,"[{'id': 324131050, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/python-cmd2/cmd2/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929', 'default': True}, {'id': 324131053, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/python-cmd2/cmd2/labels/help%20wanted', 'name': 'help wanted', 'color': '159818', 'default': True}, {'id': 324180750, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/python-cmd2/cmd2/labels/minor', 'name': 'minor', 'color': 'bfe5bf', 'default': False}]",[],0,"`preparse()` and `postparse()` methods exist in `cmd2.Cmd` and the docstrings say they get called before and after the user input is parsed. Same methods are referenced in `hooks.rst`. However, these two methods are never called the command processing loop in `onecmd_plus_hooks()`.

We need to either call these methods, or remove them from the code and the documentation.

If we decide to call these methods, we will have to make a decision about when the right time to call `preparse()`, because on a multiline command, the line can be parsed multiple times.

`postparse()` would be called at the same place as the existing `postparsing_precmd()` hook.",{},{}
