I am trying to call a function I wrote in Python via Pybind. I am trying to pass this function an array of numbers (or some class that can act as one). I would like this array to be 2d, but a flattened 1d version works fine. I would also like to be able to accept return values from this Python function in C++. These return values would also be 1d or 2d arrays of numbers.

I am having trouble with the casting and type-conversion business. For example if data is a 1d array of floats I would like to do 
`py::object my_module = py::module::import(""my_module"");
py::object f = my_module.attr(""my_function"");
f(data)`

I have tried data in both the form of a 1d array of floats and a flattened Eigen matrix. I have also tried this with 2d objects. A typical error message I receive is:
'unable to convert arguments to Python object'.

On the other hand, when returning arguments I try the following code:
` py::object f = my_module.attr(""give_me_array"");
 py::object result = f();
std::vector<int> arr = result.cast<std::vector<int>();`

where the Python code I'm calling looks something like:
`def give_me_array():
return [1,2]`
A typical error message I receive is 'unable to cast Python instance to C++ type.

I have successfully tried the basic examples provided in the documentation such as calling add(1,2) in Python from C++ which produces 3 back in C++.  I don't understand what to do when it comes to anything more than the basic built in types. I am new to C++ so sorry if I am missing a big idea here.",{},{}
