18303,IssuesEvent,2017-12-05 00:24:59+00:00,34138622,jupyter-widgets/ipywidgets,192614,jasongrout,25869250,jupyter-widgets,opened,Model spec out of date,[],[],0,"It looks like several PRs changed the model spec. We'll have to be more careful about this, perhaps with a test that generates the model spec and compares to the model spec document (which is also mostly auto-generated).

One released change:
* #1714 added `description_width` to the ToggleButtonsStyleModel without updating the spec document. This was released in 7.0.1.

Two unreleased changes:
* #1822 makes nulls not possible in the ToggleButtons.button_style (https://github.com/jupyter-widgets/ipywidgets/pull/1822/files#diff-6d34727498411c9232fd0726eb7100c7L427).
* #1834 introduces two attributes into the ToggleButtonStyleModel, `button_color` and `font_weight`. (We should also test the `button_color` one more time - the current theme I think changes the color slightly when the toggle item is selected, but `button_color` may overwrite that.)

The real question is what to do about the model spec change (which should not have been released on a patch release).

#1822 and #1834 in particular are holding up a release now.

CC @SylvainCorlay",{},{}
18306,IssuesEvent,2017-11-04 07:37:42+00:00,34138622,jupyter-widgets/ipywidgets,6559099,SimonBiggs,25869250,jupyter-widgets,opened,Request for guidance building a jupyterlab extension that makes heavy use of ipywidgets,[],[],0,"Hi @jasongrout ,

I am currently building the following jupyterlab extension:
https://github.com/SimonBiggs/jupyterlab-form

The gist of it is users can write a python enabled form in markdown. The focus is on having very small amounts of code so as not to scare off non-python users. The results of the form inputs/outputs need to be saved to json so that another extension, written later, can be trend the data etc. The markdown itself ends up being a form template that can be easily updated as needed.

I already have some basic interactivity, however I believe that what I am building would be significantly benefited by trying to leverage the work you've done with ipywidgets.

At the moment I have just two input types, number and string. Essentially when those inputs change then the python code in the same section is run. There is currently no feedback from the kernel to update those variables if their representation changes in the kernel.

Do you have recommendations of how I might be able to go about including some of the ipywidgets interfaces into my extension? Ideally the method I would use would be sufficiently decoupled so that other ipywidgets could be included at a later stage. It would be nice if I provided a simple custom tag for the major ipywidgets, but then also provided a general ipywidgets tag allowing any other ipywidget to be inserted.

What are your thoughts? Is trying to build atop of ipywidgets worthwhile, or would it be the wrong way to achieve what I am after? From what I can tell building ipywidgets into the forms achieves what I am after perfectly.",{},{}
