18705,IssuesEvent,2018-07-30 18:40:27+00:00,80946973,lark-parser/lark,11006026,kyechou,38646335,lark-parser,closed,GrammarError: Rule '...' already exists (potentially a bug),[],[],6,"Hi, I was using lark release version 0.6.2, and it seemed to falsely report errors about duplicate rules.
I can re-produce the situation with the following piece of code.

```python
from lark import Lark

grammar = ''' 
start: rule

rule: MAC ADDRESS
    | MAC_ADDRESS

MAC: ""mac""
ADDRESS: ""address""
MAC_ADDRESS: ""mac-address""

%import common.WS
%ignore WS
'''

text = 'mac address'

parser = Lark(grammar)
parser.parse(text)
```

In this case, it aborted with the message:
```
lark.exceptions.GrammarError: Rule '<NonTerminal(u'rule') : Terminal('MAC_ADDRESS')>' already exists
```
, which is seemed to be caused by the following line in `parse_tree_builder.py`.
```python
internal_callback_name = '_callback_%s_%s' % (rule.origin, '_'.join(x.name for x in rule.expansion))
```

Is this a bug? And if it is, what would be a better way to fix it?
Any help would be appreciated.",{},{}
18706,IssuesEvent,2018-07-13 06:39:06+00:00,80946973,lark-parser/lark,1703237,petermlm,38646335,lark-parser,opened,Edit the Expecting string,[],[],0,"With the given grammar:

```
from lark import Lark

grammer = """"""
    value: dict
         | list
         | ESCAPED_STRING
         | SIGNED_NUMBER
         | ""true"" | ""false"" | ""null""

    list : ""["" [value ("","" value)*] ""]""

    dict : ""{"" [pair ("","" pair)*] ""}""
    pair : ESCAPED_STRING "":"" value

    %import common.ESCAPED_STRING
    %import common.SIGNED_NUMBER
    %import common.WS
    %ignore WS
""""""

parser = Lark(grammer, start='value')
parsed = parser.parse('{""key"": $""value"", ""list"": [1, 2, 3, 4]}')
